snippet: The agreement was reached after both sides accepted the financial realities, in the face of an approaching winter.
abstract: Analysts say deal struck to restart Russian natural gas supplies to Ukraine will keep homes heated for approaching winter, but does not fully settle long-running and fierce fight over energy prices; more crucial is fact that grudging acceptance of deal does not signal imminent end to deeper political dispute over eastern Ukraine, standoff that has brought Russia and West into most dangerous conflict since Cold War.

byline.contributor: Reporting was contributed by James Kanter in Brussels, Stanley Reed in London, and Andrew Roth and Alexandra Odynova in Moscow.

lead_paragraph: The agreement was reached after both sides accepted the financial realities, in the face of an approaching winter.

headline.main: With Political Rift Still Deep, Russia-Ukraine Gas Deal Is Widely Seen as a Patch
headline.print_headline: With Political Rift Still Deep, Russia-Ukraine Gas Deal Is Widely Seen as a Patch
